									"patching_rect" : [ 10.0, 20.0, 672.0, 79.0 ],
									"text" : "[spindrift~] can create automated spatial trajectories, with circular motions ('spin'), linear motions ('drift') or even spirals. Currently, these only affect the location of the 'emitter', the virtual object that moves through space emitting grains. The grains themselves are static. (This may change in a future release)\n\nLocalization is simulated using a combination of speaker gains and changing wet/dry levels for reverb.",
									"textcolor" : [ 0.388277, 0.389862, 0.394619, 1.0 ]
								}

							}
, 							{
								"box" : 								{
									"fontname" : "Arial",
									"fontsize" : 11.0,
									"id" : "obj-2",
									"linecount" : 15,
									"maxclass" : "comment",
									"numinlets" : 1,
									"numoutlets" : 0,
									"patching_rect" : [ 225.0, 132.0, 331.0, 203.0 ],
									"text" : "DEFINITION (SAR = Speaker array radius)\n\n\nx-coordinate increment of the emitter orbital centre\n      (in SAR/sec; default = 0)\ny-coordinate increment of the emitter orbital centre\n      (in SAR/sec; default = 0)\n\n\nAngular velocity of the emitter around the emitter orbital centre\n      (in degrees/sec; default = 0)\n\n\nIncrement of the emitter distance, eg to create spiral trajectories\n      (in SAR/sec; default = 0)\n"
								}

							}
, 							{
								"box" : 								{
									"fontface" : 1,
